# Supabase Database Patterns

Conventions for `supabase/migrations/*.sql` and `apps/web/src/services/*.ts`.
The full runbook is in [docs/billing.md](../../docs/billing.md) — these rules
are the must-follow extracts. **Default-deny is the posture: clients can only
read their own rows; all writes go through service-role on the server.**

## Atomic balance / counter operations → RPC, never JS read-then-write

Any change that needs to read a value, compute, then write **must** happen
inside a Postgres `security definer` function. Two parallel webhook events for
the same user can otherwise lose a write to a stale-balance race.

```sql
-- ✅ GOOD: atomic in one transaction, idempotent on stripe_event_id
create or replace function public.grant_tokens(p_user_id uuid, p_amount int, ...)
returns int
language plpgsql
security definer set search_path = ''
as $$
begin
  -- 1. fast-path idempotency check
  -- 2. insert audit row (catch unique_violation as safety net)
  -- 3. INSERT ... ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE for atomic increment
end;
$$;

revoke all on function public.grant_tokens(...) from public;
grant execute on function public.grant_tokens(...) to service_role;
```

```ts
// ✅ GOOD: thin TS wrapper just calls the RPC
const { data, error } = await supabase.rpc("grant_tokens", { ... });

// ❌ BAD: read + compute + upsert is a race
const { data: bal } = await supabase.from("token_balances").select("balance")...;
const newBalance = (bal?.balance ?? 0) + amount;
await supabase.from("token_balances").upsert({ balance: newBalance }, ...);
```

Always include `security definer set search_path = ''`, `revoke all ... from public`,
and `grant execute ... to service_role` (or `authenticated` if a row-scoped
function the user calls directly).

## Webhook idempotency: `stripe_event_id` is the lock

Every webhook-driven write tags `token_transactions.stripe_event_id`. The
unique index makes Stripe replays a no-op. Handlers MUST be safe to replay:

```ts
await grantTokens({ ..., stripeEventId: event.id });  // returns null on dup
```

If you add a new webhook handler, write it to short-circuit on the unique
constraint, not just the pre-check — see `grant_tokens` for the pattern.

## RLS performance: wrap `auth.uid()` in a subquery

```sql
-- ✅ GOOD: evaluated once per query
create policy "Users can view own X" on public.x for select
  using ((select auth.uid()) = user_id);

-- ❌ BAD: VOLATILE function fires per row
create policy "Users can view own X" on public.x for select
  using (auth.uid() = user_id);
```

## Default-deny on sensitive tables, plus an explicit deny

Tables that hold money, entitlements, or audit logs (`stripe_customers`,
`subscriptions`, `token_balances`, `token_transactions`) should have **no**
INSERT / UPDATE / DELETE policies for `authenticated` / `anon`, plus an
**explicit deny** so the intent is unambiguous:

```sql
create policy "Deny client writes to token_balances"
  on public.token_balances for all
  to authenticated, anon
  using (false) with check (false);
```

The service-role client (used by webhooks and server actions) bypasses RLS,
so legitimate writes still work.

## Index hot jsonb metadata lookups with partial expression indexes

```sql
-- ✅ GOOD: partial keeps the index tiny
create index token_transactions_invoice_idx
  on public.token_transactions ((metadata->>'stripe_invoice_id'))
  where amount > 0;
```

Only index the rows you actually query (here: positive grants only — refund
rows are negative and irrelevant for the lookup).

## Triggers handle `updated_at`; don't set it manually in service code

`update_updated_at()` runs `before update` on every table that has an
`updated_at` column. Don't set it again in your `UPDATE` statements; the
trigger will overwrite the value anyway.

## When to add a new RPC

Add a Postgres function (RPC) when you need:
- **Atomicity** across multiple writes the client can't safely retry
  (balance + audit row).
- **Conditional writes** like "decrement only if balance ≥ amount".
- **Aggregation** that's expensive to round-trip (dashboard counters).

Don't reach for an RPC when a single Supabase query covers it.
